The standard or specification is included in 3 national catalogues. They belong to Member States which comply with at least 4 out of 5 sections of the EIF according to the NIFO factsheets. HTTP is a transfer protocol which has been developed to exchange the information through computer networks. It is supporting the first level of maturity defined by Tim Berners Lee-s 5 star schema for Open data, "Make your data available" 

See
https://5stardata.info/en

IETF has a formal review and approval so that all the relevant stakeholders can formally appeal or raise objections to the development and approval of specifications.

Each distinct version of an Internet standards-related specification is published as part of the "Request for Comments" (RFC) document series. This archival series is the official publication channel for Internet standards documents and other publications.

During the development of a specification, draft versions of the document are made available for informal review and comment by placing them in the IETF's "Internet-Drafts" directory, which is replicated on a number of Internet hosts. This makes an evolving working document readily available to a wide audience, facilitating the process of review and revision.

See:
https://www.ietf.org/standards/process/ 
https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2026

HTTP is publicly available for implementation and use, and therefore for everyone to study, for free on IETF's webpage.                                                           See:                                                                                                                                        https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2616

Like all the IETF standards, HTTP is a free and open technical specification, built on IETF standards and licenses from the Open Web Foundation. HTTP 1.1 is therefore licensed on a royalty-free basis.                                                                    

See:
https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc3668                                                                                                                                        https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2616

HTTP has ben in use by the World-Wide Web global information initiative since 1990. That fact evidences that the standard has the sufficient market acceptance and is sufficiently maturity.                                                                   See:                                                                                                                                        https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2616
HTTP is used for any solution using internet, including innovative solutions.

HTTP 1.1 is maintained by IETF which is an international community developing open standards.

See:
https://www.ietf.org/about/
HTTP allows the access to websites providing information on administrative rules, procedures and services.
As a protocol for data exchange, HTTP allows the exchange of information with interfaces of public administration systems.
HTTP is a sector agnostic specification.

HTTP is publicly available for implementation and use for free on IETF's webpage.

See:                                                                                                                                       https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2616

IETF is a vendor neutral standard developing organisation and HTTP is independent from any technology or platform.

See:                                                                                                                                       https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2616
HTTP is the main protocol underlying the world wide web. The protocol supports the exchange of high amounts of data.
HTTP (Hypertext Transfer Protocol ) is a Transfer Protocol used for communication over a computer network. It is used to transfer data between administrations.

The once-only principle is an e-government concept that aims to ensure that citizens, institutions, and companies only have to provide certain standard information to the authorities and administrations once.

HTTP is a protocol developed to exchange information over the internet environment. Thus, HTTP eases the implementation of once-only principle by means of allowing administration's stakeholders reduce interaction.    
                                                                           
See: http://www.toop.eu/sites/default/files/D21_Federated_OOP_Architecture.pdf
The purpose of HTTP is not related to  e-accessibility. Therefore this criterion is considered not applicable specification.

The specification has been creation to exchange information through the internet, it has not security layer. 

The extension of HTTP; HTTPS, uses other protocols for securing communications.
The purpose of HTTP is not related to the delivery of multilingual European public services. Therefore this criterion is considered not applicable specification.
The specification eases the access to information via webpages. Therefore, it reduces administrative burden for citizens, businesses and public administrations.
The purpose of HTTP is not related to the long-term preservation of electronic records and other kinds of information. Therefore, this criterion is not applicable to this specification
No study assessing the standard or specification in terms of effectiveness and efficiency has been found.

HTTP is already associated to an EIRA ABB in the European Library Of Specifications (ELIS). More specifically, HTTP can define the interoperability aspects of the "Network Service", "Network Component" "Private Network" and "Public Network" ABBs of the EIRA Technical View.

See: 
https://joinup.ec.europa.eu/solution/elis/distribution/eliscataloguev100betaxlsx
No mechanisms assessing the compliance of implementations with the specification have been found.

At least 11 Member States are recommending HTTP in their ICT National Catalogues.                                                                                          
See:
https://joinup.ec.europa.eu/collection/common-assessment-method-standards-and-specifications-camss/camss-list-standards

Any cross-border project using internet, uses HTTP.

An interesting example is the TESTA network service – which stands for Trans European Services for Telematics between Administrations – provides a European backbone network for data exchange between a wide variety of public administrations. It is an ISA2 solution which has been designed to support the needs for a whole range of application architectures relying on protocols such as HTTPS. 

See:
https://ec.europa.eu/isa2/solutions/testa_en

HTTP is included within at least 11 Member States' ICT Catalogues (e.g. Spain, France, Sweden)

See CAMSS List of Standards:
https://joinup.ec.europa.eu/collection/common-assessment-method-standards-and-specifications-camss/camss-list-standards

The rules on European standardisation allow the European Commission to identify information and communication technology (ICT) technical specifications - that are not national, European or international standards - to be eligible for referencing in public procurement. This allows public authorities to make use of the full range of specifications when buying IT hardware, software and services, allowing for more competition in the field and reducing the risk of lock-in to proprietary systems.

After being evaluated compliant with the regulation on standardisation 1025/2012, HTTP has been identified by Commission Implementing Decision and included in the European list of ICT Standards for e-procurement.

See: 
https://ec.europa.eu/growth/industry/policy/ict-standardisation/ict-technical-specifications_en

The rules on European standardisation allow the European Commission to identify information and communication technology (ICT) technical specifications - that are not national, European or international standards - to be eligible for referencing in public procurement. This allows public authorities to make use of the full range of specifications when buying IT hardware, software and services, allowing for more competition in the field and reducing the risk of lock-in to proprietary systems.

After being evaluated compliant with the regulation on standardisation 1025/2012, HTTP has been identified by Commission Implementing Decision. During the evaluation process, all the Member States are invited to share their doubts. The positive evaluation of HTTP and its identification is considered an interoperability agreement.

See: 
https://ec.europa.eu/growth/industry/policy/ict-standardisation/ict-technical-specifications_en

The purpose of HTTP is not related  to the modelling of business processes. Therefore, this criterion is not applicable to the specification.
The purpose of HTTP is not related to organisational interoperability. Therefore, this criterion is not applicable to the specification.
HTTP does not defines a cross-sector reusable data model. HTTPS is a transfer protocol used for secure communication over a computer network.

HTTP is an internet protocol for the data exchange over an Internet network. It supports the first level of maturity defined in the Tim Berners-Lee´s  5 stars Open Data deployment scheme, "Make your data accessible on the web".
